{
  "slug": "rangoli-tile-size",
  "title": "Rangoli Tile Size",
  "difficulty": "easy",
  "kind": "coding",
  "statement_md": "Fest week is here, and the arts club got the main courtyard to decorate. The courtyard is a rectangle, `A` metres by `B` metres. The plan is simple: cover the whole floor with identical **square** rangoli tiles, each side a whole number of metres.\n\nThree rules from the club head:\n\n- no tile gets cut\n- tiles can't overlap\n- nothing spills past the courtyard's edge\n\nBigger tiles mean fewer tiles and everyone goes home earlier. So find the side of the **largest** square tile that still covers the courtyard perfectly, and print that side length in metres.",
  "input_format_md": "The first line contains a single integer `T` — the number of courtyards.\n\nEach of the next `T` lines contains two integers `A` and `B` — the courtyard's sides in metres.",
  "output_format_md": "For each courtyard, print one integer on its own line — the side length of the largest square tile that covers it exactly.",
  "constraints_md": "- `1 ≤ T ≤ 1000`\n- `1 ≤ A, B ≤ 10^18`\n- values go up to 10^18 — use `long` in Java, `long long` in C++, and `BigInt` in JavaScript (plain numbers lose precision)",
  "hints": [
    "If square tiles of side K cover the courtyard exactly, then K must divide both A and B with no remainder. So you're really hunting for the largest number that divides both.",
    "Trying every K is hopeless at 10^18. Notice: any K that divides both A and B also divides A % B. So the answer for (A, B) is the same as for (B, A % B) — keep shrinking like that until one side hits 0, and the other side is your answer."
  ],
